segments.text: The only money they have is getting lifetime memberships, and most of them sold them too cheap.
Yeah, I expect some.
Okay, so things are really, let's say, becoming professionalized in the association and the money-raising activities.
Well, meanwhile, I developed a staff.
Ms. Shepherd got sick, and Delucia had been my neighbor over on Suffolk Street, and I didn't know her well.
I just knew her.
her as a person, and her husband was very ill at the time.
And I knew she was taking him to the hospitals a lot.
He was a veterinarian with the USDA.
And she was running, after they separated, she was running the cafeteria in the MSC.
And I had Joe Buser as editor.
And then by this time, I'd had a couple more.
We kept upgrading the magazine at the time.
Well, I tried to get that magazine in a comfortable big time.
Basically, the only criticism I've ever gotten on the magazine is we do a lot of fundraising in it.
But after all, the former student's budget is what supports the magazine.
And the foundation and the 12th Man Foundation, they pay for their ads in there.
So that magazine's expensive.
God, that printing.
And we use that color process all the time.
And oh, I want to tell you about this University of Pennsylvania.
When we got ready to print the first directory, we went directly from the address graph plates right smack into tape on the computer.
Went to the 7094, went to 709 first and then 7094.
But we went from address graph plates from a questionnaire to a punch card.
And the punch cards is how we went on tape.
So in 1966 we were getting ready to print a directory, and Frank
Cheryl from Dallas, had introduced me to a guy named Bill Mason from Flower Town, Pennsylvania, who was a pioneer in the world of photo line typesetting.
It hadn't really hit off yet, because the old cold and hot typesetters were fighting it like crazy.
And he said, it's the wave of the future.
So I called him and said, I met you in Fort Worth with Frank Cheryl, who was a typesetter.
And he said, yeah, I remember you.
I said, well, we're ready to talk to you now about setting the time for this directly.
He said, well, bring me a loop of tape up here.
And he said, come on up, spend a couple of days with me.
So I stayed with him in his house.
I'd been in a meeting in Washington with the American Alumni Council.
I took the bus up to Philadelphia.
And then he met me at the bus station and went up to his house in Florentine.
Oh, he had this damn thing.
I was really impressed with that whole thing.
So I stayed there a couple of days.
And he ran it and ran it and ran it.
Boy, it was looking good.
And he said, boy, I'm sure happy to have this book.
He had a hell of a time financing his company, because these people were too leery of him.
He was too much way ahead of his time.
And he finally went and broke them.
And I think some printers picked him up, and he survived the thing somehow.
But our book helped him.
Our book really helped.
We had the first alumni directory on Earth printed by a computer tape.
Type was set by it.
And he had those great big lights and all this stuff.
Photos were in a line.
That's why I call it a photo line typesetting.
They call it something else now.
But anyway, I stopped by the University of Pennsylvania and thanked those people for their ideas about the annual giving and their $100 and their Ben Franklin.
I said, I called mine the Century Club.
And they'd say, oh, we know all about it.
I said, you made it more successful than we did.
So I told them about my directory, and they said, who's doing that?
I said, aren't you on tape yet?
They said, yeah, we're on tape, but we're not doing much with it.
They said, we certainly don't print a directory or anything like that with it.
Who's doing it?
I said, one of your alumni named Bill Mason in the class of 1939 over in Flyertown.
They said, Bill Mason, we never heard of him.
I said, well, you can call him.
It would be nice for you to go out and visit with him and look at his setup, because he'll help you do a lot of things with your computer in the way of typesetting and design.
So that was really an interesting little sideline of getting computers done.
But those pioneer days.
So my little story, and Doug Yager was the graduate student that did the conversion from dress, graph, tooth.
See, his thesis was about like that, and for which he got all kinds of awards from IBM and everybody else.
I'd take my questionnaire and directory, and I said, here it is.
Between this questionnaire and this directory is a very, very complicated matter.
But I said, it's worth it.
That 67 book was printed by computer, and ever since then we've been doing it.
But we got really high in the computer field with that first directory.
That was real.
That's interesting.
The only woman over there that still went to Stardust is Jean Sher.
She went through it all.
She started from the very beginning in the 60s.
See, Dick left in 64.
They listed in 63, and they listed in 64.
He really left in 64.
I mean, it's got to change gears for just a second.
What was your involvement with athletic activities and programs as a former student?
Well, we had to conduct all the coaches' nights.
We took the coach around to the clubs and all that stuff, and they all wanted to see the coach, because we wanted to come and buy tickets and fill the stadium up.
That's what we were trying to do.
And get them to charter buses and bring buses, bring people in for games and all that kind of stuff.
So the involvement was fundraising for the stadium,
for the Letterman's Association.
They didn't have anything like that.
They just had a group that selected the Hall of Fame.
That's how it goes.
See, Fulberg wanted two things started.
That was a Hall of Fame and a Letterman's Association Hall of Fame and the quarterback club.
Well, the quarterback club was easy.
I just called about five guys and had lunch with them and said, here's a proposal.
And if you're interested in this, and Coach, I said, Coach Folberg is ready here to talk to you how he wants to use it.
And so they grabbed that like a, at least I got out of that.
Damn, I thought I was going to have to do that too.
Because he asked me to do it.
I said, no, I said, it's better to have volunteers do this.
That's what you want.
And so we go back to the other stuff, the Hall of Fame.
We couldn't get the Lettermen to take any interest because they wouldn't pay any dues.
Well, we had to have some dues to hire a secretary, see?
And so I was having to do that work, getting a folder printed.
See, I'm using former student money for athletics and for everything else.
Plus, we'd have to process the gifts.
People would make money to, so it was a restricted gift.
We'd have to process and write to the agency or whatever who was ever going to do the work.
Now, they had the Aggie Club was there, but nobody was doing anything with it.
We didn't even have a secretary.
We had a part-time secretary.
which was my roommate, and then Marion Pugh, and then Homer Adams was in there someplace, but he lies a lot.
And then there was John Hopkins was the first one.
When Stallings came, Stallings called me one day and said, say, oh, this is interesting.
You know this TAM?
Well, I stole that from TCU.

and you see the the thing about tcu it doesn't look very good and they were using they were using this big block t like this and they're using a c over here and u well that didn't look very damn good and so i one day i'd i'd do it like this and i wrote a m now that looks nice because you got the flow downwards see here it it looks clumsy see and so uh oh the glide folks
So anyway, I didn't say anything to anybody.
I just started using this on mailing pieces and just using it.
I didn't put it on stationery.
I was using the seal for that.
I used a former student seal, or the university seal with former students wrapped around it, see?
And I just started using this on various and sundry mailing pieces.
And I got a letter one day from Clyde Post that says, you dirty rat.
Why have you stolen our logo?
I know he found out.
I called him, and I said, Clyde, I said, I didn't steal your logo.
I said, I'm using AM instead of C. I said, your CU doesn't look good anyway.
That's not a very good looking damn thing.
I said, do you have a copyright on it?
He said, no.
I said, well, then why can't I use it?
He said, oh, hell, I know once you start it, you won't quit now.
So they then changed their logo to the one that you see they have now.
Yeah, I have seen that.
That's a good one.
They make it white on the side of their football helmets and stuff.
But anyway, this was the original.
I stole that from TCU.
Yeah, well, see, that looks good.
This looks terrible.
You would think this had been there all the time.
Hasn't.
I think I started using it in 1960.
maybe two or three early, right after I'd been here about a year.
Whenever I saw that TCU on the helmets, I thought, damn, AM would look like that.
That doesn't look right.
It would look good if you had two years under it.
Now, that might look better.
But the AM really looked nice.
And so Stallings called me and said, say, I know some of that stuff you got around here.
Willard Clark made some jewelry with it and all that stuff.
He said, could I use that on the football helmets?
I said, sure.
I said, there's no copyright on anything.
I said, now there is now, I think.
But I said, anybody, you can use it, sure.
I said, get a decal company, and I'll give you some names of them.
I always said, give that to whoever, Bones or Wally.
I guess Wally.
I said, give it to them.
So I gave them the names of these decal companies.
They'll make you the decals and show you how to mount them.
Billy Pickard will do that.
Monk Meeks, I think, was down there then.
So I was involved with the athletic department on the coaches' nights and on the meetings.
In fact, on the council meetings, we'd always have the head coach come over.
So we were interlocked.
But that proved me more and more that we got to get a full-time person with the Aggie Club.
So Stallings was all for it.
And I said, well, if you can't make the budget on painting the first year, I said, give me a budget or something, and I'll help you with money from the former students.
I said, we've got to get this off our backs.
And he said, let me look around.
So there was a classmate of his named John Hopkins.
And John was hired as the first full-time secretary for the Aggie Club.
And he had a couple assistants.
And John's problem was he got so damn authoritative, and he got so possessive.
For example, he'd hurt people's feelings.
The whole thing was wrapped around, by God, you've got to pay so-and-so, or you're done.
You've got to be more diplomatic.
When you're fundraising, you can't hurt people's feelings somehow.
You've got to kiss their ass the whole time.
They may not like the smell, but God damn it, you better have your nose plugged up like that when you kiss them.
So anyway, this is the story of TAM.
What I want to ask you, too, about the athletic thing is, did you feel much heat or pressure as director of former students from former students
who felt like the former students should exercise greater control or influence or whatever over athletic programs.
Was there a lot of rub there, a lot of pressure?
Yeah.
And they felt that we ought to have more authority, we ought to have more say, more input.
And that kind of puts you in a tight spot between the two.
I would guess it would.
I'd get my weekly phone call from a local lawyer here, and he'd say,
You son of a bitch, you've done it to me again.
And hang up the phone every time we lose a game, see?
So then I'd call back and say, now, Ed, Ed Davis, so why don't you call me?
Why don't you call the coach?
He said, hell, I can't call the coach.
He won't talk to anybody.
I can't call the president.
Hell, he'd say, this is not my thing.
I said, he said, you're the only son of a bitch I pay out there.
Your job is to get that.
That's a good point.
Every time you lose a football game, it's your goddamn fault.
So you're kind of a hang guy.
He said, why don't you fire that son of a bitch?
I bet you caught a lot of heat.
Oh, I did.
Just awful.
We were losing so much, it was changing a lot of coaches and so on.
Yeah, it was tough, tough.
My biggest problem was getting involved in the Ballard affair.
Because we had a lot of former students who were crazy about him, but liked him, hated to see him go.
But then there's the powerful boys, hated that wishbone formation.
They wanted us to use the T-set, pro-set, you know.
And the eye, oh, God, it was big.
And here, they were telling Dr. Williams, he said, we have a
Director of Athletics, which was then the coach.
That was bad.
They should never have had that.
But that's the only way they could get Bear Bryant.
Bear Bryant had been browbeaten by that basketball coach at Kentucky, see, Doc Rupp.
What is it?
Doc Ruff?
Ruff?
Ruff?
Whoever the basketball hero was there.
And so there was a lot of consternation.
Yeah, former students have always been involved.
Now, we're not so much now since the 12th Man Foundation.
Tubman now has over $18 million in endowments for the 12-man scholarships.
And that's strictly athletic.
Strictly athletic, right.
Income from that goes to the athletic department.
Dr. Williams met with them.
He said to me, he said, what should I tell these people?
And I said, Dr. Williams, I think you should tell them that the best program that they can latch onto is to
set up an endowment for every athletic scholarship.
Of course, he didn't realize they were going to have all these women's programs and all the other things.
It would double, triple the whole budget.
Now we've got a $14 million budget now for the athletic department.
That's staggering, see?
And he said, I think, he said, if the former students can endow the president's scholarships, why can't the Aggie Club endow the 12th Man Scholarship?
And so he met with their board, and that's what he told them, and that's what launched it.
Well, they had a bad guy over there.
He was a bad guy.
And so the job was open, and I helped get him fired.
He was wearing a fake Aggie ring, and so I had an anonymous photo.
The guy was not an Aggie at all?
Yeah, he'd been here for three years.
His roommate...
was Ross Margraves, who's chairman of the Board of Regents.
That was his roommate.
And Ross Margraves called someone and said, who's chairman of the Ring Committee?
They said, Buck Meyers.
And he said, well, you call him and tell him to check on Don Brister's ring.
So I called over to Registrar's office.
Now, let me tell you how secure things aren't.
I called over to Registrar's office.
Now, someone in my office, I guess, heard me talking.
And I used that name, Brister.
And I called over to Ed Cooper, to the registrar, and I said, I want you to pull a transcript of Don Brister, class 63.
And I'll be right over.
I want to look at it.
I don't want to listen to it on the phone.
So I walked over to the Koch building, and they had Brister's.
Shit, he had 68 hours.
And I don't know how many grade points, but it was pretty bad.
And he was saying, Aggie Ring, you can't order until you get 92.
It was 96 hours.
Then it's 93 hours now.
And so I walked back.
When I got back to my office, Brister was in my office.
How the hell did he know that?
See, the only people who knew were the registrar in my office.
Someone leaked.
See, can you imagine the president of the United States?
I can see now.
How are those things going to happen?
Just imagine.
I don't think you can secure anything.
under the threat of death, maybe, but I don't know how, boy.
So he was in my office, and he says, what should I do?
I said, well, number one, throw that damn ring in the Brazos River.
Divest yourself of it.
Destroy it.
Lose it.
Number two, call your president, Bob Little, in Houston, and ask him to call a board meeting, executive committee meeting from the board, and resign.
I said, you have no business walking around here with a fake Aggie ring on.
I said, that's awfully, awfully...
Devious, nothing else.
Dishonest.
It's a terrible thing.
I said, if people knew that, it would just be a scandal.
I said, let's don't have any scandal.
Let's don't publicize it.
Just resign.
Well, he called Bob Little, and they met, and of course they got rid of him.
At that time, Harry Green was flopping around out here between hotels and the real estate business.
It had gone broke under Bob Baker and the Arnold boys.
Aggieland Inn had gone under, and so I wrote a letter to Bob Little, and Bob Little told me, he said, you really fucked up that ring job.
I said, I did.
He said, yes, why didn't you call me?
I said, I didn't have a chance to.
I said, by the time I found out what his grades were and all that stuff and came back to my office, he was waiting for me there.
So I told him to bail out.
He said, well, I should have been notified first.
And I said, well, I'm sorry.
It just didn't work out that way.
I said, it wasn't that I didn't want to.
I was coming back to the office to call you.
But I saw no reason to call you with the man standing there.
And I said, he called you, didn't he?
He said, yeah, sure did.
He said, well, he said, I was just mad as hell at you for not letting me know that.
So, you know, I get help for whatever.
Yeah, I bet you did, but I have pressure in me.
No, the coaching pressure is like it is in any big school.
The alumni are in the middle of it.
The big thing is we've got the money separated, and that's good.
How about the budget of the former Students Association?
Do you remember any growth rates?
I can get the figures, but just as a general.
Well, boy, listen, when I came there, we just didn't have any money.
We had some university commitments.
We had the loan fund to administer and the student loan fund.
See, when Bob Walker went over, we moved the loan fund over.
Oh, no, no, no, no, no, no.
When the student aid office, now Rudder was good about that, except he wouldn't pay anybody anything.
When we got the student aid office set up, Bob Logan was the first one hired.
Rudder tried to hire Bob Murray, Juanita Murray's husband.
And he wouldn't give him anything, but he'd say, well, he'd been a counselor, a civilian student counselor.
And you know, they don't work much, and it's kind of a bullshit job.
But where he asked him what salary, and the runner said, well, you have to come at your same salary.
And Bob says, well, it is now.
He said, I'm given quite a bit of freedom.
He said, I'd expect to get a little raise or something.
And the runner said, it's all I can do right now, either take it or leave it.
Bob says, well, I think I'll leave it.
Well, he died a year later.
He was a World War II hero, shot all to pieces.
He had a heart attack.

So Bob Logan, we transferred the student loan program and all the opportunity where scholarships went from development to him, to the administration of all scholarships came out of the Student Financial Aid, finally where they should be.
They shouldn't be run by development.
They shouldn't be run by the former students.
They ought to be run by the university.
What was roughly the income of the former students when you came?
Do you have any idea?
Yeah, I sure do.
It's right here.
I sure do.
It's all right here.
John did a good job on this thing.
What do I got in here?
I'll be darned.
I got all kinds of crap in here.
I've used this.
I get stuff out of here for speeches all the time.
And yeah, we've got it in here someplace.
I can dig it out of there.
No, I'd like to.
What I was saying is what it was when you came and what it was when you...
Yeah, I think we got all of that.
I think we got all of that.
For the presidency.
We've even got campus muster speakers in here.
Okay, it's got to be further back in here.
Century Club memberships.
We had a total of 370 in 1977.
We had 7,347, and I don't know what we had in 1980.
Oh, no.
The year before that, we had 8,355.
We dropped.
from 76 to 77.
See, 76 was the centennial year, and that was a big point.
Yeah, that's right.
We jumped 335 between 75 and 76, so 8,355 in 76.
That's the century club memberships.
That includes the silver, bronze, silver, gold, diamond, and so on.
You retired when?
In 80.
In 80.
And what was, let's say, the income of the former Students Association in that year, roughly?
I don't even know what you mean.
We've got it in here.
I think we do, yeah.
Oh, not 1980.
This book only went to some...
I'm just saying some number that you remember that would be...
I don't remember.
You don't remember?
I'll find it, that's all right.
And most of the money, most of the income of the former students, would you say that was dedicated income?
I know you were doing the faculty awards.
for example, like we were doing with scholarships.
All that money, the money we spend is unrestricted money.
Unless someone gives to a program.
And then it's dedicated.
They give to a program.
Then that money is dedicated for that program.
It's restricted for that purpose.
What do you think has been the major, I guess you would say, accomplishment, or role, or purpose, or goal of the former Students Association in its relationship to Texas A&M?
I got it.
OK.

The greatest thing that the Association of Former Students ever did for Texas A&M University was after the long-range study I told you about that recommended we have a full-time director, that we publish a magazine, we have distinguished alumni awards, and all these programs, a magazine, and so on.
In that study, it said, however, we can't progress with our projects until the university determines its future.
Unless the university sets its goals inside and has
long-range plans on what it intends to be by the centennial in 1976, we recommend that the university have a self-study to determine its future.
That was the greatest statement ever made because the Board of Regents took that and said, OK, but will you help us?
And we said, former student says, yes, sir.
We will do two things.
They said, we think that the governor ought to appoint
a study of 100 people to the century study, which will give the goals by the completion of the century in 1976 of the university.
We'll call that the Century Council.
Half former students and half Texans.
Half of them, the former students, will recommend to the governor.
The other half, the governor should recommend himself
with a certain percentage of women.
We think women ought to be appointed to this study also.
Then the former students gave a $50,000 budget to the university to hire a full-time man in secretary, and that man was Robert L. Hunt, Jr.
I forget what he was doing at that time.
His dad was quite a beloved, famous old
I guess an agronomy professor or something like that.

And this launched a study that took a year long with subcommittee meetings and so on, and they produced the Blueprint for Progress, which outlined the recommendations of the composition of the student body, the changing of the status, the name of the university, the Anacostia Mechanic College of Texas to Texas A&M University.
And now, this is recommended to the regents by this Blueprint for Progress, which is a result of the Century Council.

That is what's set, and we recommend that the university be restructured into colleges according to degree programs, like liberal arts, like science, like agriculture, engineering, architecture, science and education, and veterinary medicine, like architecture.
See, many of these.
divisions were inside of the School of Arts and Sciences, School of Engineering, and School of something.
They were not colleges, degree-granting colleges.
So we wanted to get the university, certainly, by 76.
Well, you know how fast that was done.
It was done next year.
And we recommended also that the women be admitted.
And see, the former students had to get that resolution
passed through the council.

And that story is John Lindsay was president of the association, and Bob Latimer helped me write the resolution, because he said, let me do it, let me do it, and was recommending that we urge the board.
And then, of course, with that recommendation, the century council had the support of the former students.
You remember when that resolution came out of the former students?
In other words, you're in 64.
In 64.
Uh-huh.
When John Lindsay was, no, no, yeah, 64, that's right.

The fall council meeting, because President Rudder said, I have to have this support for the former students before we can take it to the regents, because that's the first thing the regents are going to ask me.
Because he talked with the president of BPI.
See, they'd gone through that up there.
They got the governor in.
They fired everybody.
A terrible time.
Oh, it was awful.
I don't know.
Yeah, I ran into the guy that did the BPI, one of the BPI histories, I think, and he and I compared those, and I mean, right down, even Auburn, incidentally.
Yeah, same thing.
The history was really similar.
These land-grant schools, especially in the South?
Yeah.
Let's see, 64, yeah, John H. Lindsay, Class 44, was president.
And, oh, we had some tough times around here.
I think I had more stress over that.
I went to Beaumont.
I went to Beaumont and was literally ran out of town.
I heard that story.
And I almost named the man who... Charlie Babcock.
Who nailed you.
Oh, listen, I was fired probably sometimes several times a day.
I'll get you fired.
Because they'd ask me.
See, I'd tell them what the council, what the association, what the central council.
And...
what direction the university was going.
What do you personally think?
I said, well, I really don't have a personal because of my position.
I take the position, well, now let's forget your position.
We want to know what you think.
I said, I'm totally in favor of it.
I said, this university's got to enter the next century.
We've got to admit women on a limited basis.
We can no longer be a little college where the Corps of Cadets is a student body.
And when I said that, I was just waving.
They didn't kill me.
They were so mad at me.
Do you think change has been a more difficult thing for A&M than most schools?
As it turned out, no.
It was initially.
We had about two years of hell.
What two years were those?
No.
It was...
I'll give you some... Let's see.
Uh...
You see, in 63, the Board of Directors permitted women to be enrolled on a limited basis.
Those were the tough years.
Oh, man, that was tough.
Because the first time I saw women being officially admitted in the catalog was 71.
In the catalog.
But see, meanwhile, they were coming and slipping and so on and so on.
And it was really...
Nothing was said, they were just admitted.
They applied, they were admitted.
That's what I, in the last, especially the couple of years.
Yeah, I'm trying to think.
Rudder's administration.
Yeah, 67, this one's about to come up here.
I don't think we even listed it as a thing, except this, limited basis.
I think it's, I don't think,
You know, another thing people have asked me over and over, when black students first were admitted to A&M?
And I tell them, I don't know.
Happily, I don't know.
Is that right?
Joe Busser guided the first one through, took him personally.
I've never heard that before.
Uh-huh.
Yeah.
And after that, women came in, unlimited, unlimited, 67.
Uh-huh.
Because I was so close to, because I was between Curley and Heaton, see?
And old Heaton called me and said, Bucket, call me Bucket, Bucket.
This is Lloyd.
I always called him Homer Lloyd.
I said yes, Homer Lloyd, what can I do for you?
Seven o'clock in the morning.
Bucket, Austin quit.
I said oh, oh Lloyd, I'm sorry to hear that.
I said you know Earl Rudder's really
He said, I know Bucket, but he quit.
You know, Austin never got along with me.
And I said, well yeah, what can I do for you?
He said, well what am I going to do, Bucket?
He says, I can't advertise this thing.
I said, you got anybody?
I said, sure.
He said, who is it?
I said, it's my next door neighbor.
I said, well one side of me is Charles Landweber, and on the other side of me is Ed Cooper.
He said, what's Ed doing?
I said, well you know, they kicked him around in that counseling business he really didn't like.
And he's now in the oil business and he's driving an altar.
He's got the, what's the name of that guy's name, the man who had the distributorship for Amoco here, they have another word for it, you have a consignment.
And I said, he now has Brenham and Caldwell and Bryan.
He has this whole district here that he's driving an oil truck around distributing gasoline and so on.
I said, I think he's doing OK as far as money is concerned.
But I said, he hasn't got to do that.
He's got talents.
This university needs him.
Because the registrar is a critical thinker.
We had to go big time.
